{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 13:36:20.709941", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary of Findings\\n- End-to-end connectivity between hosts exists but is degraded with significant packet loss.\\n- The routing/control plane across the Clos fabric is healthy: all BGP sessions are established, and correct prefixes are present in the RIBs/FIBs on all routers.\\n- The packet loss is caused by an artificial traffic impairment on host pc_0_0, not by the network fabric.\\n\\nObserved Symptoms\\n- Ping from pc_0_0 to pc_0_1: 25% loss (3/4 received), RTT ~1.8–3.0 ms, TTL=61.\\n- Ping from pc_0_1 to pc_0_0: 50% loss (2/4 received), RTT ~3.0 ms, TTL=61.\\n- A longer ping (50 packets) from pc_0_0 timed out due to high loss (command exceeded time limit).\\n\\nControl Plane/Routing Health\\n- BGP sessions are up on all routers:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: 2 peers up (spine_router_0_0 at 172.16.0.4, spine_router_0_1 at 172.16.0.8), each advertising 1 prefix.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1: 2 peers up (spine_router_0_0 at 172.16.0.6, spine_router_0_1 at 172.16.0.10), each advertising 1 prefix.\\n  - spine_router_0_0: 3 peers up (super_spine 172.16.0.0, leaf 172.16.0.5, leaf 172.16.0.7), has 2 prefixes.\\n  - spine_router_0_1: 3 peers up (super_spine 172.16.0.2, leaf 172.16.0.9, leaf 172.16.0.11), has 2 prefixes.\\n  - super_spine_router_0: 2 peers up (spines), has 2 prefixes.\\n- Routing tables are correct and symmetric:\\n  - Leaves have directly connected /24 and BGP-learned remote /24 via local spines.\\n  - Spines have both /24s via the appropriate leaf neighbors.\\n  - Super-spine has both /24s via a spine.\\n- Interface and IP stats on routers show no RX/TX errors or drops.\\n\\nData Plane and Host Edge Observations\\n- pc_0_0 interface configuration:\\n  - tc qdisc show dev eth0 => netem corrupt 60%.\\n  - This injects random bit-level corruption into 60% of egress packets from pc_0_0.\\n- pc_0_1 interface is normal:\\n  - tc qdisc is fq_codel (no impairment).\\n- Impact of netem corrupt on pc_0_0:\\n  - From pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: echo requests are often corrupted before leaving pc_0_0, leading to lost replies.\\n  - From pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: echo replies generated by pc_0_0 are corrupted on egress from pc_0_0, causing lost responses at pc_0_1.\\n  - This explains high bidirectional loss despite healthy fabric and consistent ~3-hop TTL of 61.\\n\\nAnomalies Detected\\n1) Major anomaly (root cause of loss)\\n- Device: pc_0_0 (host)\\n- Interface: eth0\\n- Condition: tc netem corrupt 60% configured.\\n- Effect: Significant packet corruption/loss observed in both directions of host-to-host traffic.\\n\\n2) Minor control-plane inconsistency (not impacting current reachability)\\n- On spine_router_0_1, BGP summary shows 0 prefixes received from the super-spine neighbor (172.16.0.2), while the super-spine indicates it sent 2.\\n- The spine still has both /24s via leaf neighbors, so data-plane traffic is unaffected. This may indicate a policy/filtering mismatch on that specific session.\\n\\nFault Localization\\n- Faulty component: Host pc_0_0, specifically its egress traffic shaping configuration (tc netem corrupt 60% on eth0).\\n- Network fabric (leaves, spines, super-spine) shows no evidence of faults: all BGP sessions established, correct routes installed, interface counters clean, and TTLs consistent with the expected path length.\\n\\nRoot Cause\\n- Artificial packet corruption configured on pc_0_0’s eth0 via tc netem corrupt 60%. This is directly responsible for the observed packet loss between hosts., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='0582548a-5ebd-4831-84d4-99456c00b12f'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
